  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3122" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Schuchardt,</opener>
        <p>many thanks for your postcard and your <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.87">article on Giacominos theories about Basque and Hamitic Egyptian</ref>
          </bibl> which I received today. I expect to reach the Hôtel du <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5048">Collége de France</ref>, Rue de la Sorbonne, <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.666">
Paris</placeName>, on the 12<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi>. I despatched to Paris yesterday my second supplement to <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2939">Vinson</persName> for the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5717">Revue des Bibliothèques</ref>. It will I think be longer than the first, and I have <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">already</hi> got some new matter to add when I correct the proofs. I was present on the 15<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> of October at the opening lecture of Professor <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1062">Azkue</persName> at the Instituto de Bizcaya for this semester. 4 boys and one old man. He sticks to his deadly error about <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">dai</hi>

          </foreign> etc: He says that this form and the other two of the present tense singular of the indicative of <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">izan</hi> are used at Mundaca, but though I passed through that village 5 or 6 times, and talked much about <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> while staying for some weeks at Bermeo close by, I never heard of this phenomenon. I have nearly finished my English version of the pastoral of S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi>. Helen, the 1300 lines of which I have copied during this vacation - in it there are some 30 cases of what I can only call the Béarnais <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
la</hi>, that is not the <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">la</hi> of the “forme régie positive” of <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5712">
Inchauspe</persName>, nor the <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">la</hi> which I call “participial”, synonymous with <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
laric</hi>, but a <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">la</hi> with no more apparent raison-d’être than the superfluous <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">que</hi> which always precedes the verb in Béarnais - This does not exist in any other Basque dialects, and shews the enormous influence of the <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Manechs </hi>upon their Souletin despisers. I have heard used with my own ears, in the mouths of Bizcayans and Guipuzcoans the word<hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none"> enda</hi> as a synonym of <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
eta</hi>. It seems chiefly used at the beginning of sentences, and reminds one of <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.4447">Icelandic</ref> and <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.845">Dutch</ref>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">en</hi>, English <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">and</hi> and German <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">und</hi>. I sent some months ago to <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2047">
Linschmann</persName> a list of <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.883">Armenian</ref> words very like <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">teghi</hi>, now sounded te<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">h</hi>ri, meaning <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">place </hi>is one of them - <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1054">
Arzac</persName> has <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">promised</hi> to reprint <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5681">
Capanaga</persName> in the next volume of the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5676">Euskalerria</ref>, but he does not always keep his word - I called on Consul <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2767">Sprenger</persName> at <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.119">Donostia</placeName> and found him aimiable. M<hi
            rendition="#sup">r</hi>. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2983">Webster</persName> has been much better lately. I see Canon <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1019">
Adema</persName> almost daily (38 Rue des Basques).</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours truly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
        <dateline>Bayonne, 4 November 1892.</dateline>
        <postscript>
          <p>
            <note n="1" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note> The translation of the opening of the <ref
              target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.197">Chanson de Roland</ref> made for me by the abbé <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5734">
Piarres Harizpe</persName> is very bad indeed.</p>
        </postscript>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
